messages.content:
@Tim 'mithro' Ansell @Leo Moser (mole99) 
It’s crazy — I started my gate-level simulation on **December 3rd**, and **18 days later**, today **December 21st**, I can finally see the first kernel messages… maybe in **two weeks** it’ll boot into the console.
This gate-level simulation runs against the Micron SDRAM model, so we’re simulating real SDRAM accesses.
We have two caches: a 2-way set-associative instruction cache and a direct-mapped data cache. We also have 4-way I-TLB and 4-way D-TLB MMU caches.
I can’t believe that 300k lines of Verilog generated by Yosys (thanx @Lofty) can actually work… that’s crazy.
@Leo Moser (mole99)  helped a lot with LibreLane, and his name is immortalized on the chip. Thanks, Leo Moser.

facts about my remote machine:
cpu: AMD Ryzen Threadripper 7960X s (48) @ 5.3GHz 
gpu: AMD ATI Radeon RX 470/480/570/570X/580/580X/590 
memory: 47.43 GiB / 251.20 GiB (18%)
I wouldn't have the patience to wait for that! 😛

Linux booting is great, but that’s an integration milestone, not verification.
Nobody runs full OS workloads in gate level simulation. That’s what FPGA or emulation is for (Shen & Lipasti).
